Therefore, we urge readers of this report to consider local contexts for both the strict legal framework of Ghana and the case-by-case view of appellate judges. Other potential societal tensions suggest that conditions in Western Sahara could impede the Supreme Court’s decree, making it hard to predict how Ghanaian judges will view the legality of expanding decriminalization.
There is an increasing recognition around the world that “regressive attitudes towards abortion are strongly influenced by the structure of political power.”229 For example, after abortion decriminalization in Chile, later steps made legal barriers “even more restrictive” through a “set of other laws, regulations, and ascriptions.”230 Further, the legal regulation of abortion several years before Chile implemented radical decriminalization in 2017 may mean that abortion barriers are resistant to change. For example, in 2012 violence against abortion access and a tough approach by social media to discuss abortion encouraged voters to elect a conservative government, which in turn helped prevent the repeal of restrictive measures for abortion.231 The United States continued to be caught up in such a political dynamic, even after states had legalized abortion decades ago.232 Similarly after South Africa decriminal
